"Mahmudy Gharaie M.H., Matsumoto R., Kakuwa Y., Milroy P.G.","Late Devonian facies variety in Iran: Volcanism as a possible trigger of the environmental perturbation near the Frasnian-Famennian boundary",2004,"Geological Quarterly","48","4",,"323","332",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-11344266363&partnerID=40&md5=f9334eccde9cdeb06f5603fa71e090b1","Dept. of Earth and Planetary Science, University of Tokyo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo, Japan; Graduate School of Arts and Sciences, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, Japan; Badley Ashton and Associates Ltd., Horncastle, Lincolnshire, United Kingdom","Mahmudy Gharaie, M.H., Dept. of Earth and Planetary Science, University of Tokyo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo, Japan; Matsumoto, R., Dept. of Earth and Planetary Science, University of Tokyo, Bunkyo-ku, Tokyo, Japan; Kakuwa, Y., Graduate School of Arts and Sciences, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, Japan; Milroy, P.G., Badley Ashton and Associates Ltd., Horncastle, Lincolnshire, United Kingdom","Upper Devonian successions surrounding the Frasnian-Famennian (F-F) boundary in Iran consist of mixed carbonate/silisiclastic deposits. The successions are characterized by conspicuous ferruginous limestones, clay-rich units, black shales, and mafic volcanic rocks that provide important insights into palaeoenvironmental conditions during this interval of Earth's history. An increase of kaolinite/illite ratio in clays associated with the F-F boundary suggests that increased chemical weathering was facilitated by warm and humid climatic conditions. Distinctive ferruginous-oolite deposits overlying the crucial Frasnian-Famennian boundary interval indicate a high supply rate of Fe-bearing clay originated during enhanced weathering under such climatic conditions. Black shales associated with the F-F boundary are interpreted to be the result of a high primary productivity caused by an increased influx of land-derived nutrients and regional volcanic activity. Widespread rift-related, basaltic activity along eastern Laurussia and northern Gondwana during the mid-Late Devonian is believed to have contribution to this global warming surrounding the F-F boundary.","Black shale; Frasnian-Famennian boundary; Greenhouse; Iran; Ironstone; Volcanism","black shale; facies analysis; Frasnian-Famennian boundary; global warming; greenstone; ironstone; paleoenvironment; volcanism; Asia; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Iran; Middle East; World",,,,,,"Abbott, D.H., Isley, A.E., The intensity, occurrence, and duration of superplume events and eras over geological time (2002) J. Geodynam., 34 (2), pp. 265-307; Alavi, M., Tectonostratigraphic synthesis and structural style of the Alborz Mountain system in northern Iran (1996) J. Geodynamics, 21 (1), pp. 1-33; Alavi, M., Bolurchi, M.H., Explanatory text of the Maku quadrangle map 1:250 000 (1973) Geol. Surv., , Iran, Geol. l Quadrangle, A1, Tethan; Alavi-naini, M., Paleozoic stratigraphy of Iran (1993) Treatise on the Geology of Iran, 5, pp. 1-492. , (in Farsi). (ed. A. Hushmandzadeh): Tehran; Arthur, M.A., Sageman, B.B., Marine black shales: Depositional mechanisms and environments of ancient deposits (1994) Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sc., 22, pp. 499-551; Assereto, R., The Paleozoic Formation in Central Elburz (Iran) (1963) Riv. Ital. Paleont., 69, pp. 503-543; Ashouri, A., The Devonian-Carboniferous boundary in Ozbak-kuh area (1997) GeoSciences, Sc. Quart. J., 29, pp. 46-51; Becker, R.T., House, M.R., Kellwasser Events and goniatite successions in the Devonian of the Montagne Noire with comments on possible causations (1994) Cour. Forsch. Inst. Senekenberg, 169, pp. 45-77; Buggish, W., The global Frasnian-Famennian ""Kellwasser Event (1991) Geol. Rundsch., 80 (1), pp. 49-72; Caldeira, K., Rampino, M.R., The Mid-Cretaceous superplume, carbon dioxide and global warming (1991) Geophys. Res. Lett., 18, pp. 987-990; Chen, D., Tucker, M.E., Shen, Y., Yans, J., Preat, A., Carbon isotope excursions and sea level change: Implications for the 